not to walk, but to sit in the back of a Russian rickshaw. It has a big trunk for carrying bags of groceries and is more efficient to ride than to walk. There are two other similar contraptions – one is like a cart drawn by a horse, and the other looks like a motorcycle, but is propelled by your knees pushing down a foot pedal.

A CHILD CAN PICK YOU UP

My first time in Ikhla Barag was the day that the first ever Rudy Project grand prize winner was announced by Dutch TV show Ranjenn Brace Yourself. The solemn setting, where speeches were made and the award barely fit in the hands of the young winner and his family, was commemorated with the forecast that my healing foot wouldn’t fit in my shoe in a week.

Jim Wind, ambassador and owner of The Chai Tea House knows his beer and music. If beer is your thing and it’s warm enough, there’s no better place in Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia to have the one you want than at this quaint Frankenstein-esque tea house. Probably the rarest beer you’ll find there is an IPA. But make up for that with ale or pilsner or lager. And makes it up for you with very reasonably priced drinks (tip: cocktails and beer can be purchased in any German-style beer hall across the country for 2,100) and a full selection of food.
